if(!window.NOTES_PRELOAD)window.NOTES_PRELOAD={};window.NOTES_PRELOAD["Public Law II"]={"Judicial Review": [{"id": "judicial-review", "title": "W1: Nature and Process of Judicial Review", "content": "<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>JUDICIAL REVIEW \u2014 COMPREHENSIVE REVISION NOTES</strong></span></h2>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>1. Structured Topic Overview</strong></span></h2>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 1 \u2014 NATURE OF JUDICIAL REVIEW</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Judicial review (JR) concerns checking the exercise of public power \u2014 courts examine lawfulness, not the merits of a decision</li>\n<li>JR is not the same as appeal \u2014 the courts do not substitute their own decision for that of the decision-maker; they can direct that the decision be made again correctly</li>\n<li>Four preliminary requirements: (i) amenability; (ii) procedural exclusivity; (iii) standing; (iv) time limits. Ouster clauses may also be raised by the defendant</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 2 \u2014 AMENABILITY</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Only 'public law decisions' are amenable to JR \u2014 CPR Part 54.1(2)(a)(ii): 'a claim to review the lawfulness of a decision, action or failure to act in relation to the exercise of a public function'</li>\n<li>R v Panel on Take-overs and Mergers, ex parte Datafin [1987]: a body is amenable if it exercises a public function or its functions have public law consequences \u2014 even without statutory underpinning</li>\n<li>The 'but for' test: would Parliament have had to regulate the activity if the body did not exist? Satisfied for ASA (Insurance Services [1990]) and Bar Council (Percival [1990])</li>\n<li>Failed for Jockey Club (Aga Khan [1993]) \u2014 public but not governmental; and Chief Rabbi (Wachmann [1993]) \u2014 internal religious matter</li>\n<li>Contracting out: amenable if specific statutory underpinning exists (Partnership in Care [2002]); not amenable if source of power is purely contractual (Servite Houses [2001])</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 3 \u2014 PROCEDURAL EXCLUSIVITY</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>O'Reilly v Mackman [1983]: JR is the exclusive procedure for challenging public law decisions; using any other procedure is an abuse of process</li>\n<li>Exceptions: neither party objects; claim is collateral to a private law right; mixed claims allow flexibility (Roy [1992]; Clark [2000])</li>\n<li>Public law grounds can be raised as a defence in private law proceedings (Wandsworth v Winder [1985])</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 4 \u2014 STANDING</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Applicant must have 'sufficient interest' \u2014 s 31(3) Senior Courts Act 1981</li>\n<li>IRC v National Federation of Self-Employed (Fleet Street Casuals) [1982]: two-stage approach \u2014 (1) permission stage filters busybodies; (2) full hearing considers proximity and merits</li>\n<li>Liberal trend: associations (Liverpool Taxi Fleet [1972]); pressure groups with expertise and sincere concern (Greenpeace No 2 [1994]; WDM [1995]); concerned citizens (Rees-Mogg [1995]; Dixon [1998])</li>\n<li>Limits: Rose Theatre Trust [1990] \u2014 individuals cannot gain standing collectively just by forming a group; Good Law Project [2022] \u2014 drafting aims too broadly to catch any public law error is insufficient</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 5 \u2014 TIME LIMITS AND OUSTER CLAUSES</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Time limits: claim must be filed promptly and within 3 months (CPR Part 54.5(1)); shorter limits for planning (6 weeks) and procurement (30 days)</li>\n<li>s 31(6) SCA 1981: undue delay may lead to refusal of relief if granting would cause substantial hardship or prejudice to third parties</li>\n<li>Ouster clauses: courts presume Parliament does not intend to exclude JR \u2014 Anisminic v FCC [1969]: error of law means only a 'purported determination', so the ouster does not bite</li>\n<li>Super ouster clauses: TCEA 2007 s 11 upheld (Oceana; LA(Albania)); time-limit ousters enforced at face value (Smith v East Elloe [1956])</li>\n<li>Recent legislation excludes s 3 HRA interpretive duty: Illegal Migration Act 2023 s 1(5); Safety of Rwanda Act 2024 s 3(1)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 6 \u2014 REMEDIES</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>All remedies are discretionary in nature (Walton v Scottish Ministers [2012])</li>\n<li>Prerogative orders: quashing order (invalidates); prohibitory order (prevents unlawful continuation); mandatory order (compels performance of duty)</li>\n<li>Other remedies: declaration; injunction (rare); damages (only where private law equivalent or HRA breach)</li>\n<li>'Not substantially different' test \u2014 s 31(2A) SCA 1981: court must refuse relief if outcome would not have been substantially different (Criminal Justice and Courts Act 2015)</li>\n<li>Mandatory orders: Inam [2023] \u2014 only granted where properly justified; onus on authority to explain why order should not be made</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>2. Summary Revision Tables</strong></span></h2>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 1 \u2014 Amenability: Key Cases</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Decision</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Principle</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Datafin [1987]</p></td><td><p>Self-regulatory takeover panel amenable despite no statutory powers</p></td><td><p>Governmental-type function test; 'but for' test; public law consequences sufficient</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Aga Khan [1993]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Jockey Club not subject to JR</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Public but not governmental; contractual with members; private law route available</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Wachmann [1993]</p></td><td><p>Chief Rabbi's decisions not amenable</p></td><td><p>Internal religious matters are private, not public</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Servite Houses [2001]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Housing association providing care not amenable</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Source of power purely contractual; statutory duty discharged by Wandsworth once care arranged</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Partnership in Care [2002]</p></td><td><p>Private psychiatric hospital managers amenable</p></td><td><p>Specific statutory underpinning (ongoing duty to provide treatment) made function public</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Insurance Services [1990]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>ASA amenable to JR</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>ASA's function sufficiently public in nature; 'but for' test satisfied</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 2 \u2014 Standing: Key Cases</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Outcome</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Principle</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>IRC / Fleet Street Casuals [1982]</p></td><td><p>NFSESB denied standing</p></td><td><p>Two-stage approach; mixed question of law and fact; no interest in others' tax affairs</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Rose Theatre Trust [1990]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Trust denied standing</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Individuals cannot gain standing by forming a group; each needs greater right than any citizen</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Greenpeace No 2 [1994]</p></td><td><p>Greenpeace granted standing</p></td><td><p>Expertise, reputation, genuine concern, 2,500 local members affected</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>WDM [1995]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>WDM granted standing</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Importance of rule of law; no other responsible challenger; prominent advisory role</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Rees-Mogg [1995]</p></td><td><p>Standing for Maastricht challenge</p></td><td><p>'Sincere concern for constitutional issues' sufficient</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Good Law Project [2022]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>GLP denied; Runnymede partial standing</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Drafting aims too broadly is insufficient</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 3 \u2014 Ouster Clauses</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Type</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Position</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Authority</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Complete ouster</p></td><td><p>Hostile approach; 'purported determination' doctrine means errors of law remain reviewable</p></td><td><p>Anisminic v FCC [1969]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Super ouster (TCEA s 11)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Upheld where Parliament clearly excludes review</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Oceana; LA(Albania)</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Time-limit ouster</p></td><td><p>Enforced at face value; shorter time constraints on specific decisions</p></td><td><p>Smith v East Elloe [1956]; CPR Part 54.5(3)</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>s 3 HRA exclusion</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Some legislation excludes courts' s 3 interpretive duty in JR context</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Illegal Migration Act 2023; Safety of Rwanda Act 2024</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 4 \u2014 Remedies in Judicial Review</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Remedy</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Effect</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Point</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Quashing order</p></td><td><p>Invalidates the decision; body must re-take it correctly</p></td><td><p>Most common prerogative remedy</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Prohibitory order</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Prevents unlawful continuation</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Used for rolling/ongoing unlawful conduct</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Mandatory order</p></td><td><p>Compels performance of duty; must be properly justified (Inam [2023])</p></td><td><p>Body must explain why order should not be made</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Declaration</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>States the legal position; does not compel action</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Frequently used in HRA cases</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Injunction</p></td><td><p>Orders action or restraint; interim relief at permission stage</p></td><td><p>Relatively rare in JR</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Damages</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Only where private law equivalent or HRA breach exists</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Very difficult to obtain in JR</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>3. Flashcard Q&amp;A</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Question</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Answer</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>What is the fundamental distinction between JR and appeal?</p></td><td><p>JR examines the lawfulness of the decision-making process, not the merits. Courts do not substitute their own decision but may quash and remit for the body to re-decide correctly.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What is the Datafin test for amenability?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>A body is amenable if it exercises a public function or its functions have public law consequences. The 'but for' test asks whether Parliament would have regulated the activity if the body did not exist.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>What is the O'Reilly v Mackman rule?</p></td><td><p>JR is the exclusive procedure for challenging public law decisions; using any other procedure is an abuse of process. Exceptions: neither party objects, claim is collateral, or CPR flexibility applies (Clark).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What is the 'sufficient interest' test for standing?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Under s 31(3) SCA 1981 the applicant must have sufficient interest. Mixed question of law and fact. Liberal trend includes pressure groups, concerned citizens and newly formed groups \u2014 but not those with purely manufactured interest (GLP [2022]).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>How did Anisminic [1969] neutralise the ouster clause?</p></td><td><p>The FCC committed an error of law so its decision was a 'purported determination', not a true 'determination'. The ouster clause only applied to a genuine determination, so it did not bite.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>When will a mandatory order be refused?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>The remedy is discretionary (Walton [2012]). In Inam [2023]: only granted where properly justified; burden on authority to show why order should not be made, but court may decline if compliance genuinely impossible.</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>4. Common Exam Pitfalls</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Pitfall</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Correct Position</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Treating JR as an appeal on the merits</p></td><td><p>JR only examines lawfulness. Courts quash and remit, they do not remake the decision.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Assuming statutory bodies always amenable, private bodies never</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Amenability turns on the nature of the function, not the form of the body. Datafin (non-statutory, amenable) vs Servite Houses (statutory, not amenable).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Confusing procedural exclusivity with absolute bar on private law claims</p></td><td><p>O'Reilly is the starting point but CPR dilutes strictness. Mixed claims allow flexibility (Roy; Clark). Defence use of public law points permitted (Winder).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Assuming pressure groups always or never have standing</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Depends on specific facts: expertise, genuine concern, affected members, whether anyone else can challenge (compare Rose Theatre with WDM).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Overlooking 'not substantially different' test (s 31(2A))</p></td><td><p>Even if error established, court must refuse relief if outcome would not have been substantially different \u2014 a significant bar from CJCA 2015.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Thinking ouster clauses always work</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Courts maintain strong presumption against effectiveness. Anisminic technique means errors of law generally remain reviewable.</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n"}], "Illegality and Unreasonableness": [{"id": "illegality-and-unreasonableness", "title": "W2: Illegality and Unreasonableness", "content": "<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>ILLEGALITY AND UNREASONABLENESS \u2014 COMPREHENSIVE REVISION NOTES</strong></span></h2>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>1. Structured Topic Overview</strong></span></h2>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 1 \u2014 ILLEGALITY AS A GROUND OF REVIEW</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>The fundamental principle of administrative law: a public body must not act ultra vires</li>\n<li>GCHQ \u2014 Lord Diplock: 'By \"illegality\" as a ground for JR, I mean that the decision-maker must understand correctly the law that regulates his decision-making power and must give effect to it'</li>\n<li>Categories of illegality: simple illegality (ultra vires); errors of law; errors of fact; relevant and irrelevant considerations; improper purpose; fettering discretion; unlawful delegation</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 2 \u2014 SIMPLE ILLEGALITY (ULTRA VIRES)</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>A body acts unlawfully if it goes beyond the four corners of its statutory power \u2014 AG v Fulham Corporation [1921]</li>\n<li>But a body may do what is reasonably incidental to a power it does have \u2014 Westminster Corporation v LNWR [1905]</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 3 \u2014 ERRORS OF LAW AND FACT</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Errors of law: any error of law makes the decision unlawful; no distinction between jurisdictional and non-jurisdictional errors (Anisminic [1969]; Page [1993])</li>\n<li>Errors of fact: must satisfy the four E v SSHD [2004] conditions: (1) mistake as to existing fact; (2) fact was uncontentious and objectively verifiable; (3) claimant not responsible; (4) mistake played a material part in the decision</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 4 \u2014 RELEVANT/IRRELEVANT CONSIDERATIONS AND IMPROPER PURPOSE</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Relevant considerations: decision-maker must take into account all relevant considerations and ignore irrelevant ones (Padfield [1968]; Roberts v Hopwood [1925]; Tameside [1977])</li>\n<li>Improper purpose: using power for a purpose outside the statutory scope, even if the action is within the literal terms (Padfield; Congreve v Home Office [1976])</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 5 \u2014 FETTERING DISCRETION AND UNLAWFUL DELEGATION</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Fettering discretion: a body with discretionary power must not adopt a blanket policy preventing individual consideration (British Oxygen v Board of Trade [1971]); can have a policy if genuinely open to exceptions</li>\n<li>Unlawful delegation: cannot delegate power to another body unless authorised by statute; Carltona exception for ministers' civil servants (Carltona Ltd v Commissioners of Works [1943])</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 6 \u2014 UNREASONABLENESS AND PROPORTIONALITY</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Wednesbury: a decision is unlawful if so unreasonable that no reasonable decision-maker could have made it (Wednesbury [1948]); high threshold \u2014 'perversity' or 'irrationality'</li>\n<li>Proportionality: four-stage Bank Mellat [2013] test \u2014 (1) legitimate aim; (2) rational connection; (3) minimum impairment; (4) fair balance. Applies where Convention rights engaged (Daly [2001]); may replace Wednesbury generally (Pham [2015])</li>\n<li>Sub-Wednesbury / anxious scrutiny: more intensive Wednesbury standard for fundamental rights without full proportionality (Brind [1991]; Ex parte Smith [1996]); largely superseded in HRA cases</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>2. Summary Revision Tables</strong></span></h2>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 1 \u2014 Categories of Illegality</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Category</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Principle</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Simple ultra vires</p></td><td><p>Body acts beyond the four corners of its statutory power; reasonably incidental acts are lawful</p></td><td><p>AG v Fulham [1921]; Westminster Corp v LNWR [1905]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Error of law</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Any error of law makes the decision unlawful; no jurisdictional/non-jurisdictional distinction</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Anisminic [1969]; Page [1993]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Error of fact</p></td><td><p>Must satisfy 4 conditions: existing fact, uncontentious, claimant not responsible, material</p></td><td><p>E v SSHD [2004]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Irrelevant considerations</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Must take relevant and ignore irrelevant; statute may list relevant factors</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Padfield [1968]; Tameside [1977]; Roberts v Hopwood [1925]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Improper purpose</p></td><td><p>Power used for purpose outside statutory scope even if action within literal terms</p></td><td><p>Padfield [1968]; Congreve v HO [1976]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Fettering discretion</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Cannot adopt blanket policy precluding individual consideration; can have policy if open to exceptions</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>British Oxygen [1971]; Lavender [1970]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Unlawful delegation</p></td><td><p>Cannot delegate unless authorised; Carltona exception for ministers</p></td><td><p>Barnard v National Dock Labour Board [1953]; Carltona [1943]</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 2 \u2014 Wednesbury vs Proportionality</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Feature</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Wednesbury Unreasonableness</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Proportionality</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Standard</p></td><td><p>So unreasonable no reasonable decision-maker could have made it; high threshold</p></td><td><p>Balancing exercise: proportionate means of achieving legitimate aim; more intensive review</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Origin</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Wednesbury Corporation [1948]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Bank Mellat [2013]; Daly [2001]; Pham [2015]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>When applied</p></td><td><p>Traditional JR; increasingly residual</p></td><td><p>Convention rights (HRA cases); EU law; possibly replacing Wednesbury generally</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Intensity</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Low: wide margin to decision-maker</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Higher: structured four-stage test with close scrutiny</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 3 \u2014 Proportionality: The Four-Stage Test (Bank Mellat [2013])</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Stage</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Question</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>1</p></td><td><p>Is the objective sufficiently important to justify limiting a fundamental right?</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>2</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Is the measure rationally connected to the objective?</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>3</p></td><td><p>Could a less restrictive measure have been used without unacceptably compromising the objective?</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>4</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Fair balance: do the benefits outweigh the severity of the rights interference?</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>3. Flashcard Q&amp;A</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Question</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Answer</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>What is Lord Diplock's definition of illegality?</p></td><td><p>'The decision-maker must understand correctly the law that regulates his decision-making power and must give effect to it.' Illegality means acting ultra vires.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What are the four E v SSHD conditions for error of fact?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>(1) Mistake as to existing fact; (2) fact was uncontentious and objectively verifiable; (3) appellant not responsible; (4) mistake played a material part in the decision.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>What is the Wednesbury standard?</p></td><td><p>A decision is unlawful only if so unreasonable that no reasonable decision-maker could ever have made it. A high threshold because courts defer to the primary decision-maker.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What is the difference between fettering discretion and having a policy?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>A body may adopt a policy (British Oxygen), but must remain genuinely willing to consider cases outside the policy. An inflexible rule that prevents individual consideration is unlawful.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>What is the proportionality test?</p></td><td><p>Four-stage Bank Mellat test: (1) legitimate aim; (2) rational connection; (3) minimum impairment; (4) fair balance. Applies where Convention rights engaged.</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>4. Common Exam Pitfalls</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Pitfall</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Correct Position</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Confusing illegality and irrationality</p></td><td><p>They are distinct grounds. Illegality = acting outside legal power; irrationality = quality of the decision within that power.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Applying Wednesbury to HRA / proportionality cases</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Where Convention rights engaged, proportionality is the correct standard (Daly). Wednesbury is less intensive and inappropriate.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Thinking a body can never have a policy</p></td><td><p>Bodies can adopt policies (British Oxygen). Problem arises only where policy is so rigid that genuine individual consideration is precluded.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Forgetting improper purpose can co-exist with lawful authority</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>A body may have the power but still act unlawfully if the purpose is improper (Congreve).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Overlooking minimum impairment in proportionality</p></td><td><p>Stage 3 of Bank Mellat requires considering less restrictive alternatives. Blanket measures particularly vulnerable.</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n"}], "Procedural Impropriety": [{"id": "procedural-impropriety", "title": "W3: Procedural Impropriety", "content": "<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>PROCEDURAL IMPROPRIETY \u2014 COMPREHENSIVE REVISION NOTES</strong></span></h2>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>1. Structured Topic Overview</strong></span></h2>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 1 \u2014 TWO BRANCHES OF PROCEDURAL IMPROPRIETY</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>The third GCHQ ground (Lord Diplock): (1) failure to observe procedural statutory rules; (2) failure to act fairly at common law</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 2 \u2014 FAILURE TO OBSERVE STATUTORY PROCEDURE</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Modern approach (R v Soneji [2006]): courts ask whether Parliament intended non-compliance to result in invalidity, having regard to the consequences; replaces rigid mandatory/directory distinction</li>\n<li>JN (Cameroon) v SSHD [2009]: deportation notice not specifying destination country did not invalidate \u2014 purpose was to assist in appeal and that was unimpaired</li>\n<li>R (Herron) v Parking Adjudicator [2011]: minor irregularities in road signs did not invalidate 39 penalty notices</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 3 \u2014 COMMON LAW PROCEDURAL FAIRNESS</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Duty of fairness applies to all public decisions adversely affecting rights/interests (Ridge v Baldwin [1964]; Re HK [1967])</li>\n<li>Three-step analysis: (i) has a duty arisen? (ii) what level of duty is owed? (iii) what is the content of the duty?</li>\n<li>Exceptions: national security (Hosenball [1977]); emergency (Pegasus [1989]); resource rationing (Cambridge AHA [1995]); waiver (Lloyd v McMahon [1987])</li>\n<li>Level of fairness depends on character of body, kind of question, statutory framework (Lloyd v McMahon per Lord Bridge)</li>\n<li>McInnes v Onslow-Fane spectrum: forfeiture (highest protection) through to fresh application (lowest)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 4 \u2014 CONTENT OF FAIRNESS</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Five elements: (i) notice of the case (Dunraven School [2000]); (ii) right to make representations (Andersen [1992]; Osborn [2013]); (iii) witnesses (St Germain [1979]); (iv) legal representation (Tarrant [1985]); (v) reasons (Doody [1993]; Oakley [2017])</li>\n<li>No automatic right to oral hearing (Lloyd v McMahon); but where it would assist assessment of risk it should be held (Smith and West [2005]; Osborn [2013])</li>\n<li>Reasons: no general common law duty but law moving towards requiring them as default (Oakley [2017])</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 5 \u2014 RULE AGAINST BIAS</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Justice must be seen to be done (R v Sussex, ex parte McCarthy [1924])</li>\n<li>Direct bias \u2014 financial (Dimes [1852]): automatic disqualification; extent of interest irrelevant</li>\n<li>Direct bias \u2014 non-financial (Pinochet No 2 [2000]): close connection to a party sufficient; actual bias not required; but mere membership of an organisation insufficient (Helow [2008])</li>\n<li>Indirect bias (Porter v Magill [2002]): objective fair-minded informed observer test \u2014 would they conclude there was a real possibility of bias?</li>\n<li>View formed in advance: definitive conclusion unlawful; provisional view acceptable (Quietlyn [1987]); local councillors may have political predisposition but not closed mind (Lewis v Persimmon Homes [2008]; Localism Act 2011 s 25(2))</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>2. Summary Revision Tables</strong></span></h2>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 1 \u2014 Content of Fairness: Five Elements</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Element</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Principle</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Notice of case</p></td><td><p>Most basic element; failure to inform is fundamental; must give reasonable time to respond</p></td><td><p>Dunraven School [2000]; Thames Magistrates [1974]; Bank Mellat [2013]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Representations</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No automatic right to oral hearing; written may suffice; inflexible 'no oral hearing' policy unlawful</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Andersen [1992]; Lloyd v McMahon [1987]; Osborn [2013]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Witnesses</p></td><td><p>No automatic right; depends on seriousness and nature of proceedings</p></td><td><p>St Germain [1979]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Legal representation</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No general common law right; body has discretion; Tarrant factors: seriousness, complexity, ability</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Tarrant [1985]; Hone [1988]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Reasons</p></td><td><p>No general duty but trend towards requiring reasons; Oakley: reasons should be given unless proper justification exists not to</p></td><td><p>Doody [1993]; Al Fayed [1997]; Oakley [2017]</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 2 \u2014 Rule Against Bias</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Type</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Test / Principle</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Direct \u2014 financial</p></td><td><p>Automatic disqualification; extent irrelevant; no need for actual bias</p></td><td><p>Dimes v Grand Junction Canal [1852]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Direct \u2014 non-financial</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Automatic disqualification if close connection to party; actual bias not required</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Pinochet No 2 [2000]; Helow [2008]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Indirect</p></td><td><p>'Fair-minded informed observer' test: real possibility of bias?</p></td><td><p>Porter v Magill [2002]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>View formed in advance</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Definitive conclusion unlawful; provisional view acceptable; closed mind vs predisposition</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Godden [1971]; Lewis v Persimmon [2008]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Policy bias</p></td><td><p>Only obligation: genuinely consider objections submitted</p></td><td><p>Franklin [1948]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Necessity</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>In rare cases bias overlooked if only one person empowered to decide</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Dimes [1852]</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>3. Flashcard Q&amp;A</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Question</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Answer</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>What replaced the mandatory/directory distinction?</p></td><td><p>R v Soneji [2006]: courts ask whether Parliament intended invalidity to flow from the specific non-compliance, considering purposes and consequences.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>How did Ridge v Baldwin change the law?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Swept away the judicial/administrative distinction. Relevant question became the extent of fairness required in the situation, not whether the function was judicial.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>What is the McInnes spectrum?</p></td><td><p>Runs from forfeiture (highest protection) through legitimate expectation to fresh application (lowest). Position determines level of procedural protection owed.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What is the Porter v Magill test for indirect bias?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Would the fair-minded and informed observer, having considered the facts, conclude there was a real possibility of bias? Objective perception test.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Is there a common law duty to give reasons?</p></td><td><p>No general duty (Doody; Hasan). But law is moving towards requiring reasons as the norm. Oakley [2017]: reasons should be given unless there is proper justification not to.</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>4. Common Exam Pitfalls</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Pitfall</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Correct Position</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Automatically requiring oral hearing</p></td><td><p>No automatic right. May be satisfied by written representations (Lloyd v McMahon). Oral hearing only where it materially assists (Osborn).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Treating any statutory non-compliance as invalidating</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Under Soneji, courts ask what Parliament intended. Minor irregularities causing no prejudice may be disregarded (Herron).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Confusing direct and indirect bias</p></td><td><p>Direct bias = automatic disqualification (Dimes; Pinochet). Indirect = Porter v Magill fair-minded observer test. Apply the correct test.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Assuming always a duty to give reasons</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No general duty. But factors favouring reasons: fundamental rights at stake; no right of appeal; aberrant decision; statutory requirement.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Forgetting legal representation is discretionary</p></td><td><p>No common law right (Hone). Body has discretion; courts use Tarrant factors to assess.</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n"}], "Legitimate Expectation": [{"id": "legitimate-expectation", "title": "W4: Legitimate Expectation", "content": "<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>LEGITIMATE EXPECTATION \u2014 COMPREHENSIVE REVISION NOTES</strong></span></h2>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>1. Structured Topic Overview</strong></span></h2>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 1 \u2014 NATURE AND SOURCES</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Legitimate expectation (LE) protects an expectation of procedure or substantive benefit arising from a public body's representation or established past practice (Schmidt v SoS [1969])</li>\n<li>Two ways LE arises (GCHQ per Lord Fraser): (1) express promise by or on behalf of a public authority; (2) regular practice which the claimant reasonably expects to continue</li>\n<li>Court assesses: (i) has an expectation arisen? (ii) is it legitimate? (iii) has the body lawfully frustrated it?</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 2 \u2014 PROCEDURAL vs SUBSTANTIVE</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Procedural LE: body promised or practised a particular procedure (Liverpool Taxi [1972]; GCHQ). Courts generally require compliance unless compelling public interest override</li>\n<li>Substantive LE: assurance leads person to believe they will receive a tangible benefit (Coughlan [2000]; Khan [1985]; Preston [1985]). Court can find frustration is 'abuse of power'</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 3 \u2014 THE FIVE LEGITIMACY FACTORS</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Clarity: promise must be clear, unambiguous and devoid of relevant qualification (MFK Underwriting [1990]); past practice must be well-established and well-recognised (Davies v HMRC [2011])</li>\n<li>Legality: promise must be within the authority's powers; ultra vires promise cannot generate LE (Begbie [2000]; Rowland v EA [2003])</li>\n<li>Agency: person making representation must have actual or ostensible authority (Flanagan [2002])</li>\n<li>Knowledge: generally required (Walker [2000]); exceptions in immigration/asylum context (Rashid [2005]; Ahmed and Patel [1998])</li>\n<li>Reliance: not essential but relevant; detrimental reliance makes frustration harder to justify (Bancoult [2009]; Begbie [2000])</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 4 \u2014 COUGHLAN THREE-CATEGORY FRAMEWORK</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Category A: body merely bears previous policy in mind \u2014 Wednesbury review only (Re Findlay [1985])</li>\n<li>Category B: procedural LE \u2014 procedure must be followed unless overriding reason; adequacy assessed by fairness (Liverpool Taxi; GCHQ)</li>\n<li>Category C: substantive LE \u2014 full balancing; frustration may amount to 'abuse of power' (Coughlan [2000])</li>\n<li>Categories are not hermetically sealed \u2014 each represents a point on a spectrum (Begbie per Laws LJ)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 5 \u2014 PROPORTIONALITY APPROACH</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Nadarajah [2005] per Laws LJ: promise or practice may only be denied where denial is a proportionate response to a legitimate aim in the public interest</li>\n<li>No distinction between procedural and substantive; respective force of competing interests governs</li>\n<li>Macro-political decisions encounter a 'steeper climb' (Nadarajah; Abbasi [2002]; Finucane [2019])</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>2. Summary Revision Tables</strong></span></h2>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 1 \u2014 The Five Legitimacy Factors</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Factor</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Requirement</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Clarity</p></td><td><p>Promise: clear, unambiguous, devoid of relevant qualification. Practice: well-established and recognised</p></td><td><p>MFK Underwriting [1990]; Paponette [2010]; Davies v HMRC [2011]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Legality</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Must be within the authority's powers to fulfil; ultra vires promise cannot generate LE</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Begbie [2000]; Rowland v EA [2003]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Agency</p></td><td><p>Person making representation must have authority to bind the body</p></td><td><p>Flanagan [2002]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Knowledge</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Generally required; exceptions in immigration/asylum (consistency principle)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Walker [2000]; Rashid [2005]; Ahmed and Patel [1998]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Reliance</p></td><td><p>Not essential but relevant; detrimental reliance makes frustration harder to justify as proportionate</p></td><td><p>Bancoult [2009]; Begbie [2000]</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 2 \u2014 Coughlan Three Categories</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Category</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Nature</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Standard of Review</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>A</p></td><td><p>Body merely bears previous policy in mind</p></td><td><p>Wednesbury unreasonableness only</p></td><td><p>Re Findlay [1985]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>B</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Procedural LE: promise or practice of particular procedure</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Court requires compliance unless overriding reason; fairness assessment</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Liverpool Taxi [1972]; GCHQ</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>C</p></td><td><p>Substantive LE: clear and specific promise of particular benefit</p></td><td><p>Full balancing; frustration can amount to 'abuse of power'</p></td><td><p>Coughlan [2000]; Finucane [2019]</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 3 \u2014 Key Cases</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Facts</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Outcome / Principle</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Liverpool Taxi [1972]</p></td><td><p>Town Clerk assured Association re taxi licences</p></td><td><p>Procedural LE upheld; corporation could not depart from undertaking</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>GCHQ [1985]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Long-standing consultation practice before changing staff conditions</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>LE arose from practice; overridden by national security</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Coughlan [2000]</p></td><td><p>Disabled patients promised permanent home; HA sought to close facility</p></td><td><p>Substantive LE (Category C); abuse of power to resile; promise enforced</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Begbie [2000]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Opposition spokesman promised continuation of assisted places scheme</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No LE: spokesperson not public authority; categories not hermetically sealed</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Nadarajah [2005]</p></td><td><p>Proportionality approach to LE</p></td><td><p>Promise may only be denied where denial is proportionate response to legitimate aim in public interest</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Unilever [1996]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>IR accepted late loss relief claims for 20 years then refused without warning</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>LE from settled practice upheld; clear and consistent pattern</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Finucane [2019]</p></td><td><p>Promise of public inquiry; government set up private examination instead</p></td><td><p>Macro-political; proportionate not to hold inquiry; LE not enforced</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>3. Flashcard Q&amp;A</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Question</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Answer</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>In what two ways can a LE arise?</p></td><td><p>GCHQ (Lord Fraser): (1) express promise by/on behalf of a public authority; (2) regular practice which the claimant reasonably expects to continue.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What are the three Coughlan categories?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>A: policy \u2014 Wednesbury only. B: procedural LE \u2014 compliance unless overriding reason. C: substantive LE \u2014 full balancing; frustration can be abuse of power.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Is detrimental reliance required?</p></td><td><p>Not strictly required (Bancoult [2009]; Begbie [2000]). But it is very relevant: the stronger the reliance, the harder to justify frustrating the LE.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What is the Nadarajah proportionality approach?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Promise or practice may only be denied where denial is proportionate to a legitimate aim in the public interest. No distinction between procedural and substantive.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>What is the 'macro-political' concept?</p></td><td><p>Where LE involves macro-political issues (diplomacy, national security, resource allocation), courts apply less intensive review and enforcement faces a 'steeper climb'.</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>4. Common Exam Pitfalls</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Pitfall</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Correct Position</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Treating Coughlan categories as hermetically sealed</p></td><td><p>Laws LJ in Begbie: categories are points on a spectrum; do not apply mechanically.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Assuming any promise generates enforceable LE</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Must satisfy all five legitimacy factors: clarity, legality, agency, knowledge and reliance.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Confusing procedural and substantive LEs</p></td><td><p>Procedural = right to have procedure followed. Substantive = right to the actual benefit. Different review standards and remedies.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Ignoring lawfulness of frustration as separate step</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Even where LE established, frustration may be lawful if overriding public interest. Burden on the public body.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Assuming macro-political cases automatically defeat LE</p></td><td><p>Reduces intensity of review but does not make LE non-justiciable. Must still be taken in good faith and proportionately.</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n"}], "Human Rights Act 1998": [{"id": "human-rights-act", "title": "W5: The Human Rights Act 1998", "content": "<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>THE HUMAN RIGHTS ACT 1998 \u2014 COMPREHENSIVE REVISION NOTES</strong></span></h2>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>1. Structured Topic Overview</strong></span></h2>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 1 \u2014 INCORPORATION AND STRUCTURE OF THE HRA</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>The HRA 1998 (in force 2 October 2000) incorporates most ECHR rights into domestic law; the UK's dualist system required parliamentary incorporation before Convention rights could be enforced in domestic courts</li>\n<li>ECHR rights fall into three categories: (i) absolute rights \u2014 cannot be limited by the state (Art 3, Art 4(1), Art 7); (ii) limited rights \u2014 Convention specifies circumstances for deprivation (Arts 2 and 5); (iii) qualified rights \u2014 interference permitted if prescribed by law, pursuing a legitimate aim, and necessary in a democratic society (Arts 8, 9, 10, 11)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 2 \u2014 SECTION 3: THE INTERPRETIVE OBLIGATION</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Section 3(1): courts must read and give effect to legislation 'so far as it is possible to do so' in a Convention-compatible way \u2014 a strong obligation even where language is clear and unambiguous (R v A [2001] per Lord Steyn)</li>\n<li>Limits of s 3 (Ghaidan v Godin-Mendoza [2004]): courts cannot change the substance of a provision completely; run counter to a fundamental feature of the legislation; contradict provisions; repeal or delete language; or make decisions for which the court is not equipped</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 3 \u2014 SECTION 4: DECLARATIONS OF INCOMPATIBILITY</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Where it is not possible to interpret a provision compatibly, a higher court may make a declaration of incompatibility (DOI); a DOI does not affect the validity, continuing operation or enforcement of the provision (s 4(6)) and is not binding on the parties</li>\n<li>Only higher courts listed in s 4(5) can make a DOI: Supreme Court, Court of Appeal, High Court, and Court of Protection</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 4 \u2014 SECTIONS 6 AND 7: PUBLIC AUTHORITIES AND STANDING</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Section 6(1): it is unlawful for a public authority to act in a way incompatible with a Convention right; s 6(3) defines public authorities to include courts and tribunals and 'functional' public authorities carrying out public functions</li>\n<li>Section 7: only a 'victim' of an unlawful act may bring proceedings; the victim test is narrower than the 'sufficient interest' test for JR (ECtHR Art 34 victim definition applies)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 5 \u2014 SECTION 2 AND THE ULLAH PRINCIPLE</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Section 2: courts must 'take into account' ECtHR jurisprudence when determining a Convention question; they are not bound to follow it; they must at minimum 'keep pace' with Strasbourg but are not required to go further (Ullah [2004])</li>\n<li>Section 19: before Second Reading, the minister must make a written statement of compatibility (s 19(1)(a)) or state the government wishes to proceed regardless (s 19(1)(b))</li>\n<li>Section 10: following a DOI or ECtHR judgment, a minister may by remedial order take expedited action to amend legislation; subject to parliamentary scrutiny under Sch 2</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>2. Summary Revision Tables</strong></span></h2>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 1: Categories of ECHR Rights</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Category</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Definition</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Examples</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Interference Permitted?</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Absolute</p></td><td><p>Cannot be interfered with by the state under any circumstances; no derogation or qualification possible</p></td><td><p>Art 3 (torture); Art 4(1) (slavery); Art 7 (no punishment without law)</p></td><td><p>Never</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Limited</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Convention itself specifies limited situations where deprivation is permitted; derogation under Art 15 may be possible</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Art 2 (right to life); Art 5 (liberty)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Only in specific Convention-permitted situations</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Qualified</p></td><td><p>Interference permitted if: (i) prescribed by law; (ii) pursuing legitimate aim; (iii) necessary in a democratic society (proportionate)</p></td><td><p>Art 8 (private life); Art 9 (religion); Art 10 (expression); Art 11 (assembly)</p></td><td><p>Yes, subject to three-part justification test</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 2: Key HRA Sections at a Glance</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Section</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Provision</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Cases</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>s 2</p></td><td><p>Courts must 'take into account' ECtHR judgments; not bound to follow</p></td><td><p>R (Ullah) v Special Adjudicator [2004]; Manchester CC v Pinnock [2010]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>s 3(1)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Legislation must be read compatibly 'so far as it is possible to do so'; strong obligation even where language is clear</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>R v A [2001]; Ghaidan v Godin-Mendoza [2004]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>s 4</p></td><td><p>Courts may make a DOI if provision cannot be read compatibly; does not affect validity or operation</p></td><td><p>Bellinger v Bellinger [2003]; Belmarsh (A v SSHD) [2004]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>s 6(1)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Unlawful for a public authority to act incompatibly with a Convention right</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>YL v Birmingham CC [2007]; Aston Cantlow [2003]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>s 7</p></td><td><p>Victim of unlawful act may bring proceedings; victim test from ECtHR Art 34 (narrower than JR)</p></td><td><p>\u2014</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>s 8</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Court may grant just and appropriate relief; damages subject to s 8(3)-(4)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>\u2014</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>s 10</p></td><td><p>Expedited remedial action by ministers following DOI or ECtHR judgment</p></td><td><p>\u2014</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>s 19</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Minister must make statement of compatibility before Second Reading</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Belmarsh \u2014 s 19(1)(a) statement was wrong</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 3: Section 3 Interpretation \u2014 What Courts Can and Cannot Do</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Courts CAN do under s 3</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Courts CANNOT do under s 3</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Interpret a provision even where language is clear and unambiguous</p></td><td><p>Change the substance of the provision completely</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Adopt a 'linguistically strained' interpretation</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Run counter to a fundamental feature or the 'grain' of the legislation</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Read down limiting language</p></td><td><p>Contradict other provisions in the legislation</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Read in implied words or provisions (as in Ghaidan)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Repeal or delete statutory language</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Apply the obligation to both primary and subordinate legislation whenever enacted</p></td><td><p>Make decisions for which the court is not equipped (Ghaidan limits)</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 4: Key Section 3 and Section 4 Cases</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Issue</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Outcome / Principle</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>R v A [2001]</p></td><td><p>YJCEA 1999 s 41 restricted evidence of complainant's prior sexual history; prejudiced D's Art 6 fair trial right</p></td><td><p>Lords used s 3 to read in an implied exception; s 3 is a strong obligation applying even where language is unambiguous; DOI should be a last resort</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Ghaidan v Godin-Mendoza [2004]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Rent Act 1977 Sch 1 para 2 only protected surviving heterosexual spouse from eviction; same-sex partner challenged under Arts 8 and 14</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Lords used s 3 to read in words 'as if they were his wife or husband'; broad approach: substance matters more than particular language. Limits on s 3 identified</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Bellinger v Bellinger [2003]</p></td><td><p>MCA 1973 s 11(c) used 'male and female'; challenged by trans woman under Arts 8 and 12</p></td><td><p>Lords refused s 3; 'against the grain' of the 1973 Act. Made DOI. Parliament enacted Gender Recognition Act 2004</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>A v SSHD (Belmarsh) [2004]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>s 23 ATCSA 2001 permitted indefinite detention of non-national suspected terrorists without trial</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>s 3 could not render compatible; DOI made under s 4. Government repealed s 23 and replaced with control orders</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>3. Flashcard Q&amp;A</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Question</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Answer</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>What is the difference between absolute, limited and qualified rights?</p></td><td><p>Absolute rights (e.g. Art 3) cannot be interfered with under any circumstances. Limited rights (e.g. Arts 2, 5) permit state derogation only in specific Convention-provided circumstances. Qualified rights (e.g. Arts 8, 10) may be interfered with if: (i) prescribed by law, (ii) legitimate aim, (iii) necessary in a democratic society.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What is the strength of the s 3 interpretive obligation?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Very strong (Steyn LJ in R v A): applies even where no ambiguity; Parliament rejected a more limited model; courts must strive to find compatible interpretation even if linguistically strained; DOI should be a last resort.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>What are the Ghaidan limits on s 3?</p></td><td><p>Courts cannot: change substance completely; run counter to fundamental feature or 'grain' of legislation; contradict provisions; repeal or delete language; or make decisions for which they are not equipped (per Lord Nicholls).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What is the effect of a s 4 declaration of incompatibility?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Under s 4(6): does not affect validity, continuing operation or enforcement. Not binding on parties. Essentially a signal to Parliament and government to address the incompatibility through legislation or s 10 remedial action.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Why is the 'victim' test under s 7 narrower than JR?</p></td><td><p>The s 7 victim test applies the ECtHR Art 34 definition: the applicant must be directly and personally affected. This is narrower than JR 'sufficient interest' which includes pressure groups and concerned citizens.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What is the Ullah principle?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Section 2 requires courts to 'take into account' ECtHR jurisprudence. Ullah [2004] states domestic courts must keep pace with Strasbourg but should not generally go further (the mirror principle). Some flexibility exists (Pinnock [2010]).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>What is the purpose of s 19 and can it be wrong?</p></td><td><p>Before Second Reading, the minister must make a compatibility statement (s 19(1)(a)) or state inability to do so (s 19(1)(b)). The statement can be wrong \u2014 in Belmarsh the s 19(1)(a) statement was found incorrect when a DOI was made.</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>4. Common Exam Pitfalls</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Pitfall</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Correct Position</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Treating a DOI as striking down legislation</p></td><td><p>A DOI does not affect validity, continuing operation or enforcement (s 4(6)). Parliamentary sovereignty is preserved. The DOI is a political signal, not legal nullification.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Confusing s 3 with conventional statutory interpretation</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Section 3 is much stronger: applies even where language is clear; court can adopt linguistically strained interpretations; applies to all legislation whenever enacted. Not limited to cases of ambiguity.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Thinking courts are bound by ECtHR under s 2</p></td><td><p>Courts must 'take into account' but are not bound (s 2 HRA). Must keep pace with Strasbourg but not required to go further (Ullah). Scope for dialogue and departure exists.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Forgetting that HRA remedies are not automatic</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Under s 8, court grants relief it considers just and appropriate. Damages are not automatic: subject to s 8(3)-(4) conditions and ECtHR principles.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Applying s 3 without first considering s 6</p></td><td><p>HRA framework proceeds: (1) Does s 6 make the act unlawful? (2) Is there a s 6(2) defence? (3) Can s 3 read legislation compatibly? (4) If not, s 4 DOI?</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Confusing absolute and qualified rights in proportionality</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Three-part proportionality test only applies to qualified rights (Arts 8-11). Absolute rights (Art 3) cannot be interfered with regardless of justification. Never apply proportionality to an absolute right.</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n"}], "Enforcement and Remedies": [{"id": "enforcement-and-remedies", "title": "W6: Enforcement and Remedies under the HRA 1998", "content": "<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>ENFORCEMENT AND REMEDIES UNDER THE HRA \u2014 COMPREHENSIVE REVISION NOTES</strong></span></h2>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>1. Structured Topic Overview</strong></span></h2>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 1 \u2014 SECTION 6: PUBLIC AUTHORITY LIABILITY</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Section 6(1) makes it unlawful for a public authority to act incompatibly with a Convention right; the s 6(2) statutory defence applies where the authority had no choice but to act as it did because of primary legislation</li>\n<li>The s 6(2) defence is narrowed or eliminated where s 3(1) can read the legislation compatibly \u2014 if s 3 works, s 6(2) cannot be relied upon</li>\n<li>Core public authorities (courts, government departments, local authorities) are always bound by s 6(1) in respect of all acts. Functional/hybrid public authorities are bound only for public functions (Aston Cantlow [2003])</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 2 \u2014 IDENTIFYING PUBLIC AUTHORITIES</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Aston Cantlow [2003]: factors for functional public authorities include extent of public funding, state regulation, statutory/governmental powers, and whether providing services the state would otherwise provide</li>\n<li>YL v Birmingham CC [2007]: private care home under contract with local authority was not performing a public function \u2014 relationship was contractual and commercial. Overturned for care homes specifically by Health and Social Care Act 2008 s 145</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 3 \u2014 SECTIONS 3 AND 4: INTERPRETATION AND DOIs</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Section 3(1) imposes a strong interpretive obligation; courts strive to read legislation compatibly; a DOI under s 4 is a last resort (R v A [2001])</li>\n<li>Ghaidan limits: cannot go 'against the grain'; cannot change fundamental character; but substance matters more than particular words</li>\n<li>DOIs: courts may declare incompatibility but cannot strike down legislation; Bellinger [2003] (gender recognition); Belmarsh [2004] (indefinite detention)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 4 \u2014 SECTION 8: REMEDIES AND DAMAGES</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Court may grant such relief or remedy as it considers just and appropriate: includes declarations, injunctions, quashing/prohibitory/mandatory orders, and damages</li>\n<li>Damages under s 8: only available if necessary to afford just satisfaction (s 8(3)); court must have regard to ECtHR principles; not available against Parliament or in criminal proceedings; court considers all other relief granted (s 8(4))</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>2. Summary Revision Tables</strong></span></h2>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 1: Section 6 \u2014 Public Authorities</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Type</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Definition</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Consequences</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Core public authority</p></td><td><p>Bodies whose nature is governmental (courts, tribunals, government departments, local authorities)</p></td><td><p>Always bound by s 6(1) for ALL acts, even purely private ones</p></td><td><p>Aston Cantlow [2003]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Functional / hybrid</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Bodies not entirely public but exercising some public functions</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Bound by s 6(1) only for PUBLIC functions; private acts not covered</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Aston Cantlow; YL v Birmingham CC [2007]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Purely private body</p></td><td><p>No public functions at all</p></td><td><p>Not bound by s 6(1) directly; HRA applies indirectly through courts' own s 6 duty to develop common law compatibly</p></td><td><p>YL v Birmingham CC</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 2: The HRA Enforcement Flowchart</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Step</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Question</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>If Yes</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>If No</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>1</p></td><td><p>Is the defendant a public authority under s 6(3)?</p></td><td><p>Move to step 2</p></td><td><p>No s 6(1) liability; consider indirect horizontal effect via common law</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>2</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Has the authority acted incompatibly with a Convention right (s 6(1))?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Move to step 3</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No HRA claim; no violation</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>3</p></td><td><p>Does the s 6(2) statutory defence apply?</p></td><td><p>Move to step 4</p></td><td><p>Authority is liable; move to remedies (s 8)</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>4</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Can the legislation be read compatibly using s 3(1)?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>s 6(2) defence falls away; s 8 remedies</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Court may make a DOI under s 4; no direct remedy for claimant</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 3: Section 3 vs Section 4 \u2014 Key Comparison</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Feature</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Section 3 Interpretation</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Section 4 DOI</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Effect</p></td><td><p>Renders legislation compatible; enables remedy for claimant</p></td><td><p>No effect on validity or operation (s 4(6)); no direct remedy</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Parliamentary sovereignty</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Preserved (courts interpret, not strike down)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Preserved; Parliament retains final say</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Binding on parties?</p></td><td><p>Yes \u2014 statute treated as meaning the compatible interpretation</p></td><td><p>No \u2014 DOI not binding on parties (s 4(6)(b))</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Last resort?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No \u2014 s 3 should be used first</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Yes \u2014 only made where s 3 compatible reading is impossible</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Who can make it?</p></td><td><p>All courts and tribunals</p></td><td><p>Only higher courts in s 4(5): SC, CA, HC, Court of Protection</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 4: Key Cases on s 3 and s 4</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Issue</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>s 3 or s 4?</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Principle</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>R v A [2001]</p></td><td><p>YJCEA s 41 restricted sexual history evidence; prejudiced D's fair trial</p></td><td><p>s 3 used</p></td><td><p>Courts must strive to find compatible reading; linguistically strained interpretation appropriate; DOI is last resort</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Ghaidan [2004]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Rent Act only protected heterosexual survivors</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>s 3 used</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Read in words 'as if they were his wife or husband'; substance over language; s 3 limits identified</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Bellinger [2003]</p></td><td><p>MCA 1973 'male and female'; incompatible with Arts 8/12 for trans people</p></td><td><p>s 4 DOI</p></td><td><p>Too far against the grain; complex reform needed; Parliament better placed (GRA 2004 followed)</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Belmarsh [2004]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>s 23 ATCSA: indefinite detention of non-national suspects</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>s 4 DOI</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Incompatible with Art 5(1) and Art 14; could not be read compatibly; major constitutional significance</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Hooper [2005]</p></td><td><p>Widowers' tax allowances discriminated against men</p></td><td><p>s 6(2) considered</p></td><td><p>Where statute imposes a duty, s 6(2)(a) applies; where discretion, s 6(2)(b) applies; both override s 6(1)</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>3. Flashcard Q&amp;A</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Question</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Answer</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>What is the s 6(2) statutory defence?</p></td><td><p>Under s 6(2)(a): defence applies where primary legislation imposed an absolute duty (no choice). Under s 6(2)(b): applies where authority was giving effect to provisions that cannot be read compatibly. Both defeated if s 3 can read the legislation compatibly (Hooper [2005]).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What factors identify a 'functional public authority'?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>From Aston Cantlow and YL: extent of public funding; state regulation; statutory powers; providing services the state would otherwise provide; exercising governmental power.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Why did the care home in YL fail the test?</p></td><td><p>The majority held the relationship was contractual and commercial. The home's acts were not intrinsically governmental. Overturned for care homes specifically by Health and Social Care Act 2008 s 145.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>When should courts use s 3 rather than s 4?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Section 3 should always be attempted first: courts must strive to find a compatible reading (R v A). DOI only made when s 3 compatible reading is impossible \u2014 i.e. where s 3 would go against the grain (Bellinger; Ghaidan limits).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>What are the limits on damages under s 8?</p></td><td><p>Only available if necessary to afford just satisfaction (s 8(3)); must have regard to ECtHR principles; not available against Parliament; court considers all other relief granted.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Does a DOI give the claimant a remedy?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No. A DOI does not affect validity or operation (s 4(6)), is not binding on parties, and provides no direct remedy. Claimant's options: ECtHR or await legislative reform under s 10.</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>4. Common Exam Pitfalls</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Pitfall</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Correct Position</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Thinking a DOI strikes down legislation</p></td><td><p>A DOI does not affect validity, continuing operation or enforcement (s 4(6)). Parliamentary sovereignty fully preserved.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Applying s 6 without checking if defendant is a public authority</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Always identify first: core or functional public authority under s 6(3). If purely private, s 6 does not arise directly; consider indirect horizontal effect.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Forgetting the s 6(2) defence</p></td><td><p>Where statute leaves authority no choice, s 6(2)(a) is a complete defence. Must be addressed before concluding unlawful action.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Using s 3 without reference to Ghaidan limits</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Section 3 has clear limits: cannot change substance, go against the grain, contradict provisions, or require decisions the court is not equipped to make.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Assuming all courts can make DOIs</p></td><td><p>Only higher courts in s 4(5): Supreme Court, Court of Appeal, High Court, and Court of Protection.</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n"}], "Articles 2, 3 and 5": [{"id": "articles-2-3-5", "title": "W7: ECHR Articles 2, 3 and 5", "content": "<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>ECHR ARTICLES 2, 3 AND 5 \u2014 COMPREHENSIVE REVISION NOTES</strong></span></h2>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>1. Structured Topic Overview</strong></span></h2>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 1 \u2014 ARTICLE 2: RIGHT TO LIFE</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Article 2 imposes three obligations: (1) negative \u2014 refrain from intentionally killing except in Art 2(2) circumstances; (2) positive \u2014 take reasonable preventive measures to protect individuals from real and immediate risk to life (Osman v UK [1998]); (3) investigative \u2014 conduct effective official investigation into deaths involving state agents (McCann v UK [1995])</li>\n<li>Art 2(2) strictly construed: force must be 'no more than absolutely necessary' (stricter than proportionality); limited to: (a) defence from unlawful violence; (b) lawful arrest/prevent escape; (c) quelling riot/insurrection</li>\n<li>McCann established that the planning of an operation must itself comply with Art 2 \u2014 lack of care in planning or control can itself violate Art 2, even where the individual soldiers were acquitted</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 2 \u2014 ARTICLE 3: PROHIBITION OF TORTURE</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Art 3 is an absolute right: no derogation or limitation possible even in wartime (Art 15); no balancing against state interests</li>\n<li>Threshold hierarchy (Ireland v UK [1978]): torture (most severe \u2014 deliberate, very serious, cruel suffering) > inhuman treatment (severe mental/physical suffering) > degrading treatment (humiliates/debases). Minimum level of severity must be crossed, assessed contextually</li>\n<li>Art 3 and expulsion: absolute prohibition \u2014 state cannot expel where real risk of Art 3 treatment in receiving state; no balancing against national security (Soering v UK [1989]; Chahal v UK [1996])</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 3 \u2014 ARTICLE 5: RIGHT TO LIBERTY</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Art 5 is a limited right: deprivation of liberty only in the six exhaustive categories in Art 5(1)(a)-(f); must be 'in accordance with a procedure prescribed by law' and 'lawful'</li>\n<li>Procedural guarantees: right to reasons (5(2)); promptly before a judge (5(3)); habeas corpus equivalent (5(4)); compensation for unlawful detention (5(5))</li>\n<li>Belmarsh (A v SSHD [2004]): indefinite detention of non-national suspected terrorists under ATCSA 2001 s 23 incompatible with Art 5(1) and Art 14; derogation under Art 15 failed \u2014 measures not 'strictly required' and discriminatory</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>2. Summary Revision Tables</strong></span></h2>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 1: Article 2 \u2014 Obligations and Exceptions</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Obligation / Exception</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Content</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Negative obligation</p></td><td><p>State agents must not intentionally kill; lethal force must be no more than absolutely necessary; planning must comply with Art 2</p></td><td><p>McCann v UK [1995]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Positive obligation</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Take reasonable preventive measures to protect individuals from real and immediate risk to life known to authorities</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Osman v UK [1998]; LCB v UK [1998]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Investigative duty</p></td><td><p>Effective official investigation into deaths involving state agents; must be independent, adequate, capable of identifying those responsible</p></td><td><p>McCann [1995]; R (Amin) v SSHD [2003]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Art 2(2)(a)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Defence of any person from unlawful violence \u2014 'absolutely necessary', stricter than proportionality</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>McCann [1995]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Art 2(2)(b)</p></td><td><p>Lawful arrest or prevention of escape \u2014 must be absolutely necessary</p></td><td><p>Strictly applied</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Art 2(2)(c)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Quelling riot or insurrection \u2014 strictly construed</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Not engaged unless organised violent insurrection</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 2: Article 3 \u2014 Threshold Hierarchy</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Level</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Definition / Standard</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Torture</p></td><td><p>Deliberate inhuman treatment causing very serious and cruel suffering; requires official sanction or acquiescence; highest threshold</p></td><td><p>Ireland v UK [1978]; Aksoy v Turkey [1996]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Inhuman treatment</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Severe mental or physical suffering not reaching torture level; includes detention conditions and interrogation techniques</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Ireland v UK; R (Limbuela) v SSHD [2005]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Degrading treatment</p></td><td><p>Humiliates or debases the victim; arouses fear, anguish, inferiority; lowest Art 3 threshold</p></td><td><p>Tyrer v UK [1978]; Price v UK [2001]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Minimum severity</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Must be crossed before Art 3 engaged; assessed by duration, physical/mental effects, victim's sex, age and health</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Ireland v UK [1978]</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 3: Article 3 and Expulsion \u2014 Key Cases</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Facts / Issue</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Principle</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Soering v UK [1989]</p></td><td><p>US national faced extradition; would face 'death row phenomenon'</p></td><td><p>Art 3 prohibits expulsion where real risk of Art 3 treatment; absolute \u2014 no balancing against offence or requesting state interests</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Chahal v UK [1996]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Sikh activist faced deportation on national security grounds; risk of torture in India</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Prohibition is absolute regardless of threat person poses to national security; no balancing permitted</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>R (Limbuela) v SSHD [2005]</p></td><td><p>Asylum seekers denied support; forced to sleep rough</p></td><td><p>State's own acts causing destitute conditions could reach degrading treatment threshold; positive obligation to prevent Art 3 conditions</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>N v UK [2008]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>HIV-positive applicant resisted expulsion; no treatment available in Uganda</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Very high threshold for medical cases; Art 3 does not require contracting states to provide medical treatment to all aliens</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 4: Article 5 \u2014 Permitted Exceptions and Guarantees</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Provision</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Content</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Art 5(1)(a)</p></td><td><p>Lawful detention following conviction by a competent court</p></td><td><p>Standard post-conviction imprisonment</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Art 5(1)(b)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Lawful arrest for non-compliance with court order or obligation prescribed by law</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>\u2014</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Art 5(1)(c)</p></td><td><p>Lawful arrest on reasonable suspicion of offence, to prevent offence, or prevent absconding (with Art 5(3) promptness guarantee)</p></td><td><p>Fox, Campbell and Hartley v UK [1990]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Art 5(1)(d)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Detention of a minor for educational supervision or appearance before a competent legal authority</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>\u2014</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Art 5(1)(e)</p></td><td><p>Lawful detention of persons of unsound mind, alcoholics, drug addicts or vagrants</p></td><td><p>Winterwerp v Netherlands [1979]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Art 5(1)(f)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Immigration/deportation detention: to prevent unlawful entry or for deportation/extradition</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Chahal v UK; A v UK [2009]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Art 5(2)</p></td><td><p>Right to be informed promptly and in simple language of reasons for arrest and any charge</p></td><td><p>Fox, Campbell and Hartley</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Art 5(3)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Person detained under 5(1)(c) must be brought promptly before a judge; right to trial within reasonable time or release</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Brogan v UK [1988] \u2014 4 days 6 hours too long</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Art 5(4)</p></td><td><p>Right to take proceedings to determine lawfulness of detention speedily by a court with power to order release</p></td><td><p>Weeks v UK [1987]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Art 5(5)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Right to enforceable compensation for unlawful detention</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>\u2014</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 5: The Belmarsh Case \u2014 A v SSHD [2004]</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Issue</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Decision</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Provision at issue</p></td><td><p>Section 23 ATCSA 2001: indefinite detention without charge of non-national suspected terrorists who could not be deported due to Art 3</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Art 15 derogation</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>UK derogated from Art 5; HoL accepted public emergency existed</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Discrimination / Art 14</p></td><td><p>Scheme applied only to non-nationals; comparable British suspects not detained; discrimination unjustified</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>'Strictly required' test</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Indefinite detention failed: less restrictive alternatives available; belied by fact British nationals not detained</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Outcome</p></td><td><p>DOI under s 4: s 23 ATCSA incompatible with Arts 5(1) and 14; government repealed s 23, replaced with control orders (PTA 2005)</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>3. Flashcard Q&amp;A</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Question</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Answer</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>What does 'no more than absolutely necessary' mean in Art 2(2)?</p></td><td><p>A stricter standard than 'necessary in a democratic society'. Force must be strictly proportionate to the Art 2(2)(a)-(c) aims. Any force beyond what is absolutely necessary violates Art 2. Planning must also comply (McCann).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What three obligations does Art 2 impose?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>(1) Negative: refrain from intentionally killing except Art 2(2) cases. (2) Positive: take reasonable preventive measures against real and immediate risks to life. (3) Investigative: effective official investigation into deaths involving state agents (McCann; Amin).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Is Art 3 a qualified or absolute right?</p></td><td><p>Absolute. No derogation under Art 15 and no balancing against state interests. Prohibition on expulsion to face Art 3 risk applies regardless of the danger the person poses (Chahal [1996]).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What threshold must be crossed for Art 3?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Minimum level of severity (Ireland v UK). Assessed contextually: duration, physical/mental effects, victim's sex, age, health. Hierarchy: degrading (lowest) \u2192 inhuman \u2192 torture (highest).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>What are the six Art 5(1) categories?</p></td><td><p>(a) post-conviction; (b) non-compliance with court order; (c) reasonable suspicion of offence (with 5(3) guarantee); (d) minor for educational supervision; (e) persons of unsound mind, alcoholics, drug addicts, vagrants; (f) immigration detention.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Why did s 23 ATCSA fail in Belmarsh?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Not 'strictly required' under Art 15: government failed to detain comparable British suspects, showing measures not truly necessary. Detention of only non-nationals was discriminatory under Art 14 read with Art 5(1).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>What is the Soering principle?</p></td><td><p>Art 3 prohibits expelling/extraditing where real risk of Art 3 treatment in receiving state. Absolute \u2014 no balancing against offence seriousness or requesting state interests (Chahal; Al-Saadoon v UK [2010]).</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>4. Common Exam Pitfalls</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Pitfall</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Correct Position</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Treating Art 2 as a qualified right subject to proportionality</p></td><td><p>Art 2 is limited, not qualified. Art 2(2) exceptions are exhaustive and strictly construed. Standard is 'absolutely necessary' \u2014 stricter than proportionality.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Confusing Art 2 planning obligation with individual soldier conduct</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>McCann shows UK violated Art 2 because overall planning and control was inadequate, even where individual soldiers were acquitted.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Thinking Art 3 can be balanced against national security</p></td><td><p>Art 3 is absolute. No balancing and no derogation (Chahal). Even the most dangerous terrorist cannot be expelled to face Art 3 risk.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Applying Art 3 without checking minimum severity threshold</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Not every ill-treatment violates Art 3. Must cross minimum severity (Ireland v UK). Assess context, then identify which level is relevant.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Treating Art 5 categories as open-ended</p></td><td><p>The six Art 5(1) categories are exhaustive and strictly construed. Do not treat Art 5 as subject to general proportionality.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Forgetting Art 5 procedural guarantees</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Art 5 is not just about initial lawfulness. Arts 5(2)-(5) provide ongoing guarantees: reasons (5(2)), promptly before judge (5(3)), challenge detention (5(4)), compensation (5(5)).</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n"}], "Articles 6 and 7": [{"id": "articles-6-7", "title": "W8: ECHR Articles 6 and 7", "content": "<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>ECHR ARTICLES 6 AND 7 \u2014 COMPREHENSIVE REVISION NOTES</strong></span></h2>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>1. Structured Topic Overview</strong></span></h2>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 1 \u2014 ARTICLE 6: RIGHT TO A FAIR TRIAL</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Art 6(1) provides the overarching right to a fair and public hearing within a reasonable time by an independent and impartial tribunal established by law; applies to determination of (i) civil rights and obligations and (ii) criminal charges \u2014 not purely administrative decisions (Bank Mellat [2013])</li>\n<li>Access to justice must be effective, not merely theoretical (Airey v Ireland [1979-80]); critical question on legal aid: whether an unrepresented litigant can present their case effectively and without obvious unfairness (Gudanaviciene [2014])</li>\n<li>Independence and impartiality (Findlay v UK [1997]): tribunal must be independent (appointment, tenure, freedom from pressure) and impartial (subjective: personal prejudice; objective: sufficient guarantees to exclude legitimate doubt)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 2 \u2014 RIGHT TO SILENCE AND SELF-INCRIMINATION</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Right to silence: implicit in Art 6 (Funke v France [1993]); adverse inferences can be drawn from silence (Murray v UK [1996]) but jury direction must limit inference-drawing to cases where silence can only sensibly be attributed to having no answer (Condron v UK [2001])</li>\n<li>Self-incrimination (Saunders v UK [1997]): prosecution must prove case without evidence obtained by coercion in defiance of the accused's will; does not prohibit using evidence from separate pre-existing processes (breathalyser, regulatory inspection)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 3 \u2014 ARTICLE 7: NO PUNISHMENT WITHOUT LAW</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Art 7 prohibits: (i) conviction for act not criminal at time; (ii) heavier penalty than available at time of offence; (iii) laws not sufficiently clear for foreseeability. A non-derogable right (Art 15 cannot override)</li>\n<li>Law must be accessible and foreseeable: SW v UK [1995] \u2014 even common law offences satisfy Art 7 if there was a 'perceptible line of case-law development' making criminalisation reasonably foreseeable</li>\n<li>Art 7(2) international law exception: person may be tried for acts criminal under general principles of law recognised by civilised nations \u2014 covers war crimes, genocide, crimes against humanity</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>2. Summary Revision Tables</strong></span></h2>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 1: Article 6 \u2014 Structure and Scope</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Sub-Article</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Content</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Scope</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Art 6(1)</p></td><td><p>Fair and public hearing; within reasonable time; independent and impartial tribunal</p></td><td><p>Both civil and criminal; includes access to justice, impartiality, timely process</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Art 6(2)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Presumption of innocence</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Criminal proceedings only; governs pre-trial publicity, burden of proof</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Art 6(3)(a)</p></td><td><p>Right to be informed promptly of nature and cause of accusation</p></td><td><p>Criminal only; read with Art 6(1)</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Art 6(3)(b)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Right to adequate time and facilities to prepare defence</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Criminal only</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Art 6(3)(c)</p></td><td><p>Right to legal assistance; right to free legal aid where interests of justice require</p></td><td><p>Criminal proceedings; also civil where effective access requires it (Airey)</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Art 6(3)(d)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Right to examine witnesses; right to call witnesses on equal terms</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Criminal; hearsay rules; Al-Khawaja and Tahery v UK [2012]</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 2: Article 6 \u2014 Key Cases</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Issue</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Principle</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Airey v Ireland [1979-80]</p></td><td><p>Could not afford representation for complex High Court proceedings</p></td><td><p>Art 6(1) requires effective access; positive obligation to provide legal aid or simplify procedure may arise</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Benham v UK [1996]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Imprisoned for non-payment of poll tax; no legal aid</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Violation of Art 6(1)/6(3)(c): severity of penalty and complexity of law required representation</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Gudanaviciene [2014]</p></td><td><p>Immigration cases; Director of Legal Aid set too high a threshold</p></td><td><p>Critical question: whether unrepresented litigant can present case effectively and without obvious unfairness</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Findlay v UK [1997]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Convening officer dominated court martial system</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Court martial violated Art 6(1): not independent or impartial</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Murray v UK [1996]</p></td><td><p>Denied lawyer for 48 hours; adverse inferences drawn from silence</p></td><td><p>Art 6 applies at preliminary investigation; lawyer must be provided where adverse inferences can be drawn</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Condron v UK [2001]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Drug addicts advised by solicitor not to answer; jury direction too broad</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Jury direction must limit inferences to where silence only attributable to having no answer</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Saunders v UK [1997]</p></td><td><p>Compelled to answer DTI inspectors; transcripts used at criminal trial</p></td><td><p>Right not to incriminate oneself: prosecution cannot use evidence obtained by coercion in defiance of accused's will</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Othman v UK [2012]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Deportation to Jordan where torture evidence might be used against him</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Art 6 violated: risk of torture evidence used constituted flagrant denial of justice</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 3: Article 7 \u2014 Key Requirements and Cases</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Requirement</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Content</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>No retrospective offences</p></td><td><p>Cannot convict for act not criminal at the time</p></td><td><p>Varvara v Italy [2013]; GIEM SRL v Italy</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No heavier retrospective penalty</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Penalty must not exceed what was available at time of offence; applies to substantive penalties, not procedural</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Scoppola v Italy (No 2) [2011]; Welch v UK [1995]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Accessibility</p></td><td><p>Criminal law must be accessible so persons know what is prohibited</p></td><td><p>SW v UK [1995]; Kafkaris v Cyprus [2008]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Foreseeability</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Law must be sufficiently precise for foreseeability; common law satisfies this if 'perceptible line of case-law development'</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>SW v UK [1995]; Del Rio Prada v Spain [2012]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Engel criteria</p></td><td><p>Three criteria for 'criminal': (1) domestic classification; (2) nature of offence; (3) severity of potential penalty</p></td><td><p>Engel v Netherlands [1976]</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Art 7(2) exception</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Person may be tried for acts criminal under international law \u2014 war crimes, genocide, crimes against humanity</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Streletz, Kessler and Krenz v Germany; Kononov v Latvia</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 4: Right to Silence \u2014 Comparison of Key Cases</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Facts</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Outcome / Distinction</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Murray v UK [1996]</p></td><td><p>NI terrorist case; denied lawyer 48 hrs; adverse inferences drawn under NI legislation</p></td><td><p>No violation re inferences (strong evidence; judge explained reasoning); violation re representation \u2014 lawyer required at initial stage</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Condron v UK [2001]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Drug addicts in withdrawal; solicitor advised silence; jury direction too broad</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Violation: jury direction must limit inferences to where silence only sensibly attributable to having no answer</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Saunders v UK [1997]</p></td><td><p>Compelled to answer DTI inspectors; transcripts used at trial</p></td><td><p>Violation: right not to self-incriminate; prosecution cannot use coerced evidence. Does not apply to evidence from other processes (breathalyser, regulatory)</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Magee v UK [2001]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Prolonged interrogation in solitary; no solicitor; confession extracted</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Violation: oppressive interrogation without legal advice vitiates voluntariness; solicitor needed as counterweight</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>3. Flashcard Q&amp;A</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Question</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Answer</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>What proceedings does Art 6 cover?</p></td><td><p>Art 6(1) covers determination of (i) civil rights and obligations and (ii) criminal charges. Does not apply to purely administrative decisions not determining civil rights or charges (Bank Mellat [2013]).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What is the 'effective access' principle?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>From Airey [1979-80]: effective access to courts must be available, not merely theoretical. Where proceedings too complex for unrepresented litigant, state may be required to provide legal aid. Critical question (Gudanaviciene): whether unrepresented litigant can present case effectively and without obvious unfairness.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>What does Art 6 require for impartiality?</p></td><td><p>From Findlay [1997]: tribunal must be (i) independent (appointment, tenure, freedom from pressure) and (ii) impartial (subjective: personal prejudice; objective: sufficient guarantees to exclude legitimate doubt).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>When can adverse inferences be drawn from silence?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Murray v UK: not automatically a violation; right to silence is not absolute. Condron v UK: jury direction must limit inferences to where silence can only sensibly be attributed to having no answer, not other reasons (solicitor's advice; health).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>What is the Saunders principle?</p></td><td><p>Art 6(1) includes right not to self-incriminate. Prosecution must prove case without evidence obtained by coercion in defiance of accused's will. Does not prohibit evidence from other processes (breathalyser, regulatory inspection) not obtained through coercion.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What three requirements does Art 7 impose?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>(1) No retrospective offences. (2) No heavier retrospective penalty. (3) Accessibility and foreseeability: law must be accessible and precise enough to foresee consequences (SW v UK).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>How did SW v UK show common law satisfies Art 7?</p></td><td><p>Applicant argued marital rape was not an offence when committed. ECtHR held common law had developed along a 'perceptible line of case-law development' dismantling the immunity. Recognition of absence of immunity was 'reasonably foreseeable' \u2014 satisfying Art 7.</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>4. Common Exam Pitfalls</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Pitfall</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Correct Position</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Treating Art 6 as applying to all public body decisions</p></td><td><p>Art 6 only applies to determination of civil rights and obligations and criminal charges. Purely administrative decisions outside Art 6 (Bank Mellat).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Assuming Art 6 requires legal aid in all proceedings</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No general right to free legal aid. Required only where necessary for effective access: severity of penalty, complexity of law, and litigant's ability are relevant (Airey; Benham; Gudanaviciene).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Treating right to silence as absolute</p></td><td><p>Murray makes clear it is not absolute. Adverse inferences permitted, but subject to Condron safeguards.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Confusing Saunders with blanket ban on real evidence</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Saunders only prohibits evidence obtained through coercion in defiance of accused's will. Does not prohibit body samples or evidence from separate regulatory proceedings.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Applying Art 7 to procedural changes</p></td><td><p>Art 7 applies to substantive criminal law, not procedural changes. Retrospective procedural change does not violate Art 7 unless it effectively alters penalty severity.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Forgetting Art 7(2) international law exception</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Art 7(1) is subject to Art 7(2): acts criminal under international law (war crimes, genocide, crimes against humanity) can be prosecuted even if not in domestic law at the time.</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n"}], "Articles 8 and 10": [{"id": "articles-8-10", "title": "W9: ECHR Articles 8 and 10", "content": "<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>ECHR ARTICLES 8 AND 10 \u2014 COMPREHENSIVE REVISION NOTES</strong></span></h2>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>1. Structured Topic Overview</strong></span></h2>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 1 \u2014 ARTICLE 8: RIGHT TO RESPECT FOR PRIVATE AND FAMILY LIFE</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Art 8(1) protects four interests: private life, family life, home and correspondence; key objective is protection against arbitrary state interference (Costello-Roberts v UK [1995])</li>\n<li>'Private life' is given wide meaning: physical and moral integrity (Costello-Roberts), personal identity and pictures (Von Hannover v Germany [2004]), human dignity (McDonald v UK [2014]), sexual orientation (Dudgeon v UK [1982]), gender recognition (Bellinger), searches of the person (Gillan and Quinton v UK [2010])</li>\n<li>'Family life' extends beyond marriage to de facto ties (Kroon v Netherlands [1995]); immigration decisions disrupting the family unit engage Art 8 (Quila v SSHD [2011])</li>\n<li>'Home' \u2014 no right to be provided with a home, but home life must be respected (Coughlan); includes quality of home life e.g. noise (Hatton v UK [2002])</li>\n<li>'Correspondence' \u2014 letters, emails, texts; interception without clear legal framework violates Art 8 (Malone v UK [1985]; Khan v UK [2001]); workplace monitoring (Copland v UK [2007])</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 2 \u2014 ARTICLE 8(2): JUSTIFICATION</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Art 8 is qualified: interference permitted if (i) in accordance with the law (accessible and foreseeable \u2014 Sunday Times v UK [1979-80]); (ii) pursuing a legitimate aim under Art 8(2); (iii) necessary in a democratic society (proportionate \u2014 Handyside v UK [1976])</li>\n<li>State surveillance must be governed by clear statutory safeguards (Khan; RIPA 2000); blanket retention policies may be disproportionate (S and Marper v UK [2008]; R (Wood) v Commissioner of Police [2009])</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 3 \u2014 ARTICLE 10: FREEDOM OF EXPRESSION</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Art 10 protects the freedom to hold opinions and to receive and impart information and ideas without interference; a qualified right subject to the same three-part justification test</li>\n<li>Handyside v UK [1976]: freedom of expression applies to ideas that 'offend, shock or disturb' \u2014 demands of pluralism, tolerance and broadmindedness</li>\n<li>Political and journalistic expression receive the strongest protection (Simms [2000]; Goodwin v UK [1996]); commercial and artistic expression receive less; racist or terrorist rhetoric receives least</li>\n<li>Section 12 HRA gives additional protection: courts must have 'particular regard' to the importance of freedom of expression</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 4 \u2014 INDIRECT HORIZONTAL EFFECT AND MISUSE OF PRIVATE INFORMATION</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Courts as public authorities (s 6 HRA) must develop common law compatibly with Convention rights (Douglas v Hello [2001]); no free-standing cause of action between private parties</li>\n<li>Breach of confidence evolved into 'misuse of private information' (Campbell v MGN [2004]); two-stage test: (1) reasonable expectation of privacy? (2) balance Arts 8 and 10</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>2. Summary Revision Tables</strong></span></h2>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 1: Article 8 \u2014 The Four Protected Interests</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Interest</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Scope</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Private life</p></td><td><p>Physical/moral integrity; personal identity and pictures; human dignity; sexual orientation; gender recognition; searches of person</p></td><td><p>Costello-Roberts; Von Hannover; McDonald; Dudgeon; Bellinger; Gillan and Quinton</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Family life</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Not restricted to marriage; encompasses de facto ties; immigration decisions disrupting family unit</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Kroon v Netherlands; Quila v SSHD</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Home</p></td><td><p>No right to be provided with home, but home life must be respected; quality of home life (noise, nuisance)</p></td><td><p>R (Coughlan); Hatton v UK</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Correspondence</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Letters, emails, texts; workplace calls and emails; prisoners' legal correspondence receives high protection</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Malone v UK; Copland v UK; R (Daly) v SSHD</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 2: Article 8(2) \u2014 Justification Framework</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Limb</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Test</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>'In accordance with the law'</p></td><td><p>Law must be accessible and foreseeable; executive discretion must not allow arbitrary action</p></td><td><p>Sunday Times v UK; Gillan and Quinton; Khan v UK</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Legitimate aim</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>National security; public safety/economic well-being; prevention of disorder/crime; protection of health/morals; protection of rights/freedoms of others</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Art 8(2) exhaustive list</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>'Necessary in a democratic society'</p></td><td><p>Must answer 'pressing social need'; proportionate to legitimate aim; fair balance between general interest and individual rights</p></td><td><p>Handyside v UK; Soering</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 3: Article 8 \u2014 Key Case Law</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Facts / Decision</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Principle</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Gillan and Quinton v UK [2010]</p></td><td><p>Broad stop-and-search powers under Terrorism Act 2000 ss 44-47</p></td><td><p>Powers not 'in accordance with the law' \u2014 unfettered discretion and lack of safeguards</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Khan v UK [2001]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Hidden listening device in hotel; no statutory framework</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Surveillance only lawful where clear statutory framework exists</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>S and Marper v UK [2008]</p></td><td><p>Blanket retention of DNA/fingerprints of cleared suspects</p></td><td><p>Blanket and indiscriminate retention disproportionate; failed to account for presumption of innocence</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Quila v SSHD [2011]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Ban on marriage visas where either party under 21</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Legitimate aim accepted, but disproportionate: impacted more unforced than forced marriages</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>R (Daly) v SSHD [2001]</p></td><td><p>Blanket policy of searching prisoner cells in absence; privileged legal correspondence read</p></td><td><p>Chilling effect on prisoner communications; blanket policy disproportionate</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>R (Nicklinson) v MoJ [2014]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Paralysed applicant sought declaration that assisted suicide lawful</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Parliament inherently better qualified to assess compatibility; declaration declined</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 4: Article 10 \u2014 Types of Expression and Level of Protection</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Type of Expression</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Level of Protection</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Political opinion</p></td><td><p>Highest \u2014 narrow margin of appreciation; strict scrutiny</p></td><td><p>Bowman v UK; Simms; Prolife Alliance v BBC</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Journalistic / press freedom</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Very high \u2014 'chilling effect' doctrine; source protection vital</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Goodwin v UK; Jersild v Denmark; Financial Times v UK</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Right to receive and impart information</p></td><td><p>High \u2014 but no general right to 'freedom of information'</p></td><td><p>Open Door Counselling v Ireland; Kennedy v Charity Commission</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Artistic expression</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Protected, but wider margin on morals</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Muller v Switzerland; Wingrove v UK</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Commercial information</p></td><td><p>Lower protection than political or journalistic</p></td><td><p>Colman v UK</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Racist or terrorist rhetoric</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Low \u2014 unless contributes to wider public debate</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>M'Bala M'Bala v France; Brind and McLaughlin v UK</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 5: Article 10 \u2014 Key Case Law</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Facts / Decision</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Principle</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Handyside v UK [1976]</p></td><td><p>Publisher convicted under Obscene Publications Acts</p></td><td><p>Expression that 'offends, shocks or disturbs' is protected; protection of morals accepted with wide margin</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Simms [2000]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Near-blanket ban on journalists interviewing prisoners</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Freedom of speech is 'the lifeblood of democracy' and a 'safety valve'</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Open Door Counselling v Ireland [1992]</p></td><td><p>Absolute injunction prohibiting information about abortion services</p></td><td><p>Absolute injunction disproportionate; both right to impart and receive information engaged</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>R (Farrakhan) v SSHD [2002]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Nation of Islam leader banned from entering UK</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Ban proportionate: justified by community relations, not merely views held; other channels available</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>R (Lord Carlile) v SSHD [2014]</p></td><td><p>Iranian dissident excluded; invited to address Parliament</p></td><td><p>Art 10 engaged; interference proportionate given UK's relationship with Iran</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>R (Laporte) v CC Gloucestershire [2006]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Coaches of protesters turned back from RAF Fairford</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No imminent breach of peace once anarchists removed; premature, indiscriminate and disproportionate</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>DPP v Ziegler [2021]</p></td><td><p>Protesters obstructed highway to disrupt arms fair; acquitted</p></td><td><p>Arts 10/11 protection extends to deliberate disruption; peaceful, targeted, limited-duration protest</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Animal Defenders International v UK [2013]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Ban on TV political advertising upheld</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Blanket ban within margin of appreciation; justified by protecting democratic process</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Jersild v Denmark [1995]</p></td><td><p>Journalist convicted for aiding racist remarks during critical interview</p></td><td><p>Conviction disproportionate; journalist engaged in proper, critical journalism</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 6: State Surveillance and Art 8</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Facts</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Outcome</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Khan v UK [2001]</p></td><td><p>Hidden device in hotel; no statutory framework</p></td><td><p>Violation: clear statutory framework required</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>R (Wood) v Commissioner [2009]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Police photos of peaceful demonstrator retained</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Violation: retention disproportionate once no crime apparent</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Wilson v Metropolitan Police [2021]</p></td><td><p>Undercover officer infiltrated groups; sexual relationships; RIPA too broad</p></td><td><p>Violations of Arts 3, 8, 10, 11, 14; RIPA authorisations not 'in accordance with the law'</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>S and Marper v UK [2008]</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Blanket DNA/fingerprint retention of acquitted suspects</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Disproportionate: failed to account for presumption of innocence</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Table 7: Misuse of Private Information \u2014 Art 8 vs Art 10 Balancing</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Stage</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Test</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>1. Is Art 8 engaged?</p></td><td><p>Does claimant have 'reasonable expectation of privacy'? Is information obviously private? Would reasonable person find disclosure offensive?</p></td><td><p>Campbell v MGN (Lord Hope); Murray v Express Newspapers</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>2. Balancing exercise</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>If Art 8 engaged, balance competing rights in Arts 8 and 10; consider whether publication was necessary</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Campbell v MGN; Von Hannover v Germany</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Cause of action</p></td><td><p>No free-standing HRA cause of action between private parties; breach of confidence evolved into misuse of private information</p></td><td><p>Campbell v MGN; Wainwright v Home Office</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Public domain</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No reasonable expectation for information already public; but waiving some privacy does not open all aspects to scrutiny</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Browne v Associated Newspapers; McKennitt v Ash</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>3. Flashcard Q&amp;A</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Question</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Answer</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>What four interests does Art 8(1) protect?</p></td><td><p>Private life, family life, home and correspondence. The key objective is protection against arbitrary state interference.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What is the three-part justification test under Art 8(2)?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Interference must be: (i) in accordance with the law (accessible and foreseeable \u2014 Sunday Times); (ii) pursuing legitimate aim in Art 8(2); (iii) necessary in a democratic society (pressing social need, proportionate \u2014 Handyside).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>How wide is 'private life' under Art 8?</p></td><td><p>Very wide: physical/moral integrity, personal identity and pictures, human dignity, sexual orientation, gender recognition, searches of person. Categories are not closed.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What did Gillan and Quinton establish?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Broad stop-and-search powers not 'in accordance with the law' \u2014 insufficient safeguards against arbitrary interference. Executive discretion must not be expressed in unfettered terms.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>What does Art 10(1) protect?</p></td><td><p>Freedom to hold opinions and to receive and impart information and ideas without interference. Includes words, pictures, images and actions intended to express ideas (Handyside).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What key principle did Handyside establish?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Freedom of expression applies to ideas that 'offend, shock or disturb' \u2014 demands of pluralism, tolerance and broadmindedness in a democratic society.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Which types of expression receive strongest protection?</p></td><td><p>Political expression and journalistic/press freedom. In Simms, called 'the lifeblood of democracy.' Commercial and artistic expression receive less protection.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What additional protection does s 12 HRA provide?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Courts must have 'particular regard' to the importance of freedom of expression when considering relief that might affect Art 10 rights.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>What is 'indirect horizontal effect'?</p></td><td><p>Courts (as s 6 public authorities) must develop common law compatibly with Convention rights (Douglas v Hello). No free-standing HRA action between private parties, but rights can be 'hung' on pre-existing causes of action.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What is the two-stage test for misuse of private information?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>(1) Reasonable expectation of privacy? (Is information obviously private? Would reasonable person find disclosure offensive?) (2) If Art 8 engaged, balance Arts 8 and 10 and consider whether publication was necessary (Campbell v MGN).</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>4. Common Exam Pitfalls</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Pitfall</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Correct Position</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Treating Art 8 or Art 10 as absolute rights</p></td><td><p>Both are qualified. Always apply the three-part justification test: prescribed by law, legitimate aim, necessary in a democratic society.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Assuming all expression receives equal protection</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Political and journalistic expression receive strongest protection with narrowest margin. Commercial and artistic receive less. Racist/terrorist rhetoric receives least unless contributing to public debate.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Forgetting less intrusive means in proportionality</p></td><td><p>Proportionality requires considering less restrictive alternatives. Blanket measures particularly vulnerable (Open Door; Quila; S and Marper).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Treating Farrakhan/Lord Carlile as broad speaker ban authority</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Both turned on specific weighty factors (community relations / national security). Do not support general principle of excluding controversial speakers on speculation.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Assuming surveillance justified by crime prevention alone</p></td><td><p>Clear statutory framework with adequate safeguards required (Khan; RIPA). Blanket surveillance/retention may be disproportionate (S and Marper; Wood; Wilson).</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Overlooking s 12 HRA in Art 10 problems</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Always mention s 12: courts must have 'particular regard' to importance of expression. Reinforces high threshold for restrictions.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Confusing negative and positive Art 8 obligations</p></td><td><p>Art 8 primarily negative (do not interfere), but also positive obligations to protect private/family life (Hatton \u2014 noise; Evans). No right to be provided with a home.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Ignoring indirect horizontal effect in private disputes</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Courts must develop common law compatibly with Convention (s 6; Douglas v Hello). Cause of action is misuse of private information (Campbell), not HRA directly.</p></td>\n</tr><tr>\n<td><p>Failing to address margin of appreciation</p></td><td><p>Margin varies: narrow for political expression and core private life; wider for morals, resource allocation, national security. Always identify which applies.</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n"}]};
